If splitting is how we break data into bite-sized pieces, Embedding is how we translate those pieces into a language an AI can understand: Math.
An Embedding turns a chunk of text into a long list of numbers (a "Vector"). This vector represents the semantic meaning of the text. Because it's math, we can calculate how "close" two ideas are, even if they don't share any of the same words.
1. How Embeddings Work
In standard search, searching for "canine" won't find "dog." In an Embedding Space, the vectors for "canine" and "dog" will be geometrically close to each other.
The Two Core Methods
In LangChain, every embedding provider follows a standard interface with two methods:
 * embed_documents: Used during ingestion. It turns your thousands of text chunks into vectors to be stored in a database.
 * embed_query: Used during retrieval. It turns a user's single question (e.g., "How do I use Pydantic?") into a vector so it can be compared against your stored documents.
2. Using Embeddings in LangChain
In 2026, there are many providers. Here is how you use a modern model like OpenAI's text-embedding-3-large or Google's Gemini Embedding 2.
from langchain_openai import OpenAIEmbeddings

# 1. Initialize the model
# 'text-embedding-3-large' is a top-tier choice in 2026
embeddings_model = OpenAIEmbeddings(model="text-embedding-3-large")

# 2. Embed a single query (for search)
query_vector = embeddings_model.embed_query("What is data validation?")

# 3. Embed a list of documents (for storage)
doc_vectors = embeddings_model.embed_documents([
    "Pydantic is a data validation library.",
    "LangChain helps build LLM applications."
])

print(f"Vector size: {len(query_vector)}") # Usually 1536 or 3072 dimensions

